ce:section.ce:para:
We selected three premium coal samples in China: Fenxi (FX), a high-volatile bituminous coal (V = 36.87%, daf), Ximing (XM); a low-volatile bituminous coal (V = 15.18%, daf), Xiaofalu (XFL); and an anthracite (V = 5.01%, daf). Proximate and ultimate analyses (GB/T 212-2008, GB/T 476-2008 and GB/T 214-2007) were conducted and mean-maximum vitrinite reflectance (Ro,

                        max) (GB/T 6948-2008) was measured (Table 1
                        ). To obtain aromatic structural parameters in processing and interpreting XRD and Raman data of coal structure, we needed to remove the minerals in coal with acid dissolution; the details of the demineralization procedures can be found elsewhere [18,19]. The coal samples were effectively demineralized, containing less than 0.5% residual minerals.

All demineralized coals were scanned by a Rigaku D/max 2500 VK/PC X-ray diffractometer, using Cu Kα radiation at 40 kV and 100 mA with a graphite monochromator (λ = 0.15406 nm). Measurements were recorded from 2θ = 10 to 80° at a scanning speed of 2°/min. The interlayer spacing (d002
                           ), crystallite height (Lc
                           ), crystallite diameter (La
                           ) and average number of aromatic layers (Nave
                           ) were calculated using the empirical Braggs and Scherrer equations [20–26].

Fig. 1
a shows the background-subtracted XRD patterns of the three demineralized coal samples with different metamorphism, which exhibit features characteristic of coal: the (0 0 2) plane (π-band) around 26°, γ-sideband near 20° and (10) plane around 45° [25,28,29]. The intensity of the (0 0 2) peak increased with the degree of metamorphism, and the peak angle slowly shifted to the lower angle side, corresponding with an increase in lattice ordering, consistent with the increase of coalification. The (0 0 2) band indicates the interlayer spacing of aromatic nuclei. The (10) band is in the high scattering angle region (~43°) of the XRD spectrum, which is close to the graphite (1 0 0) band and is used to evaluate the average diameter (La
) of aromatic nuclei in coal. The (γ) band is on the left-hand side of the (0 0 2) band, representing a saturated structure; this could include aliphatic side chains, which are grafted to the edges of the aromatic nuclei, prompting the (0 0 2) band to appear as obvious asymmetrical characteristics [23,28].

The aromatic nuclei structure cannot be directly determined by the correlation characteristics of the original XRD spectrum's diffraction peaks, but the peak positions, intensity, area and full width at half maximum (FWHM) can be obtained after fitting (0 0 2), (γ), and (10) diffraction peaks. Fig. 1b–d show the curve-fitting of three Gaussian peaks for the three coal samples. The calculated structural parameters of all samples are listed in Table 2
                        . The aromaticity (fa) for the three coal samples range from 0.66 to 0.88. The crystallite height (Lc
                        ) and crystallite diameter (La
                        ) of the aromatic nuclei structures, measured using the Scherrer formula range from 17.55 to 22.49 Å and 11.41 to 21.79 Å, respectively (Table 2). The d002
                         of the aromatic nuclei ranges from 3.64 to 3.51 Å; the Nave
                         vary from 4.8 to 6.4; the coalification degree (p) is 0.54, 0.68, and 0.75 for the XM, XF, and XFL samples, respectively. The increase in rank is associated with an increase in spatial ordering, which is manifested by the decrease of d002
                         and the increase of lattice parameters (La
                        , Lc
                        , and Nave
                        ).

Some of the organic matter in the three coals were digested under the strong oxidation of a concentrated sulfuric/nitric acid mixed solution at 100 °C, while the aromatic nuclei were retained because they are difficult to oxidize. Fig. 3
                        a–c shows the TEM images of the aromatic cluster obtained. Most of the aromatic clusters were irregularly round and well dispersed. We can judge against the TEM observations that there is a significant correspondence between aromatic cluster size and coal rank. The higher the coalification, the wider the aromatic cluster diameter. We have observed more than 10 regions for each sample, and the total number of spots per coal is more than 500. The statistical results (Fig. 3d) obtained using the NanoMeasure software demonstrate that the aromatic cluster size of high-volatile bituminous coal FX is the smallest; the smallest and largest diameters are 1.10 and 4.63 nm, respectively. The total content of the aromatic cluster was between 2 and 3 nm and was above 53%. The aromatic cluster size of low-volatile bituminous coal XM increases slightly, mainly concentrating around 2–4 nm, with the smallest and largest diameters being 1.59 and 7.76 nm, respectively. Anthracite XFL has the largest aromatic cluster size and the broadest distribution, ranging from 2.21 to 10.17 nm and mainly concentrating in the range of 3–6 nm (see Table 4
                        ).
